Access feature presence/absence.¶

As we stated, a feature is deemed present when missing values of a feature accounts for less than 50% of sample space, all sample or within each group.

In [8]:
d1$nacount <- as.matrix(apply(d1, 1, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))) #count the missing signal values by feature
d1$nacount_Native = as.matrix(apply(d1[, 1:6], 1, function(x) sum(is.na(x))))
d1$nacount_Semi = as.matrix(apply(d1[, 7:12], 1, function(x) sum(is.na(x))))

Missing data imputation.¶

We are gonna impute both datasets, because their missing value percentages are both low enough. We will use k-nearest neighbors for imputation. This is how we decide k, square root of number of features.

In [11]:
# decide K (how many neighbor to use)
k <- d2_2 %>% length() %>% sqrt() # square root of number of features
if (k>=3){
        if (is.integer(k)) k = k else k = ceiling(k)
} else {k = 3}

k
4

This data distribution looks normal based on histogram and qq plot, so we will stop here and proceed with univariate and multivariate analysis.

Other normalization methods include rank invariant normalization implemented using lumi, cubic spline normalization implemented using affy. If normalization step cannot transform the data to a near Gaussian distribution, we will follow up with scaling step, implemented using MetaboAnalyze.

Univariate analysis, t-test and Wilcoxon rank sum test.¶

In [21]:
d5 <- rbind.data.frame(labels_d1, norm_d1)

C <- d5[-1,which(d5[1,]=="Naive")]; P <- d5[-1,which(d5[1,]=="Semi_immue")]

wt <- data.frame(Doubles=double(),Doubles=double(),Doubles=double(),Doubles=double(),Doubles=double())

# Calculate p-values from both t-test and Wilcoson rank sum test. 
# P-values will need to be adjusted with Benjamini-Hochberg correction (i.e., FDR)
for (i in 1:dim(norm_d1)[1]){
        wt[i,1] <- t.test(type.convert(t(P[i,])),type.convert(t(C[i,])))$p.value
        wt[i,3] <- wilcox.test(type.convert(t(P[i,])),type.convert(t(C[i,])))$p.value
        az1 <- 2^(type.convert(C[i,])); az1L <- length(az1)
        az2 <- 2^(type.convert(P[i,])); az2L <- length(az2)
        wt[i,5] <- gtools::foldchange(sum(az2)/az2L, sum(az1)/az1L)
        #print(az1)
}
wt[,2] <- as.data.frame(p.adjust(wt[,1], method = 'BH'))#, n = length(p))
wt[,4] <- as.data.frame(p.adjust(wt[,3], method = 'BH'))#, n = length(p))

colnames(wt) <- c("pT", "BHT", "pW", "BHW", "FC(lin)")
row.names(wt) <- rownames(norm_d1)

# Calculate log2FoldChange
log2FoldChange =gtools::foldchange2logratio(wt$`FC(lin)`,base = 2)
wt = cbind(wt,log2FoldChange)
head(wt)

Score plot¶

In [25]:
ggplot(pca, aes(PC1, PC2,colour=Label)) + geom_point() + stat_ellipse() +
        xlab(paste("PC1", round(pc@R2[1] * 100, digits = 1), "% of the variance")) +
        ylab(paste("PC2", round(pc@R2[2] * 100, digits = 1), "% of the variance"))

As is shown in score plot, there are clear separation between these two groups, and the first PC accounts for ~74% of total variance of the dataset. The ellipses represent 95% confidence intervals.
